<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: THOUSAND OAKS; WORK UNDER WAY ON NEW AUTO MALL SIGN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MATTHEW MOSK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Construction of the fiercely contested Thousand Oaks Auto Mall sign has begun 
with the recent installment of a support structure along the Ventura Freeway. 
</P>
<P>
 Sign designer Scott Bailey of Newbury Park-based Signature Signs said work on 
the 20-foot-tall display officially got under way three weeks ago and will be 
completed in June. 
</P>
<P>
 "This is not your average sign," Bailey said. "There's a lot more to it." 
</P>
<P>
 The sign, which was the focus of several months of vocal debate in the City 
Council, is the product of a compromise between the auto mall and nearby 
residents. 
</P>
<P>
 Bailey said the stucco-and-tile structure will include five terraced planters 
with live plants, an irrigation system, an energy-efficient temperature and 
time display, and the globe logo for the auto mall. 
</P>
<P>
 The sign board, he said, will not be much different in size from the existing 
274-square-foot brown and white sign that it replaces. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think when people finally see it, they will say to themselves, 'Oh, this is 
not such a big deal after all,' " Bailey said. MATTHEW MOSK 
</P>
</TEXT>
