<P>
BASEBALL / DAILY REPORT; ANGELS; RODGERS HAPPY WITH CATCHERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELLIOTT TEAFORD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Manager Buck Rodgers was so concerned about the Angels' catching last season 
that he kept three catchers, hoping one would emerge as an everyday starter. It 
never happened, but he has become more comfortable with Greg Myers and Chris 
Turner, who will share the job this season. 
</P>
<P>
 "I have more confidence in both of them," Rodgers said Sunday. "I don't think 
it will ever come down to a strict platoon. 
</P>
<P>
 "Right now, it's probably 50-50. I may lean 60-40 toward somebody." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The Angels' starting lineup for opening day against the Minnesota Twins on 
Tuesday at the Metrodome is expected to look like this: 
</P>
<P>
 Chad Curtis, center field; Damion Easley, third base; Tim Salmon, right field; 
Chili Davis, designated hitter; Bo Jackson, left field; Eduardo Perez, first 
base; Myers, catcher; Harold Reynolds, second base; Gary DiSarcina, shortstop; 
Mark Langston, pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The Angels trimmed their roster to 25 by assigning relief pitcher Ken 
Patterson to their minor league camp. They also purchased the contracts of 
pitchers John Dopson, Bob Patterson and Bill Sampen, all non-roster invitees to 
spring training. ELLIOTT TEAFORD 
</P>
