<HEADLINE>
<P>
APARTMENT FIRE FORCES 29 RESIDENTS TO FLEE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A suspected arson fire swept through a two-story apartment building and a 
duplex in Downtown Los Angeles on Sunday, forcing 29 people out of their homes. 
</P>
<P>
 The fire started about 3 a.m. in a car inside a garage. "It looks like 
somebody torched the car," said Los Angeles Fire Department spokesman Bob 
Collis. 
</P>
<P>
 The fire quickly spread through the occupied building to the empty duplex next 
door on South Orchard Avenue, Collis said. 
</P>
<P>
 Fifty-five firefighters battled the blaze, which was extinguished in about 30 
minutes. No injuries were reported. 
</P>
<P>
 The Red Cross issued motel vouchers to all 29 displaced people and plans to 
help the families relocate if necessary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
